  "why": "The paper enforces semantic consistency and naturalness in its fuzzing design. LipFuzzer mutates seed voice-command templates using learned linguistic models (LAPSUS Models) that encode realistic speech-error patterns via Bayesian Networks trained from a user study, and it uses probability/hop cutoffs to restrict mutations to likely, plausible variants. The system performs at most a single, model-guided mutation per seed (preventing iterative accumulation/drift) and verifies candidates by synthesizing speech with platform TTS (Amazon Polly / Google Cloud TTS) before testing on real VA devices. These elements (learned plausible mutation distribution, cutoff-based selection, single-step mutation, and real TTS verification) together demonstrate both semantic consistency where applicable and control of naturalness.",
